{"term":"1976","caseName":"Morris v. Gressette","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1976/75-1583","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 19, 1977","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/15592","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will resume arguments in 1583.","start":0,"stop":3.204,"duration":3.2},{"text":"Mr. Bell.","start":3.204,"stop":9.893,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief justice, and may it please the court.","start":9.893,"stop":15.361,"duration":5.47},{"text":"We are astonished that anyone could come in to this court and suggest, as we understood counsel, yesterday to suggest first that South Carolina is deliberately evading the provisions of Section 5 for Voting Rights Act in this case, and second the Attorney General in 1972 did not look at the submission of our senate plan.","start":15.361,"stop":39.376,"duration":24.01},{"text":"We believe that both of these suggestions are flatly contradicted by the record in this case.","start":39.376,"stop":46.481,"duration":7.11},{"text":"It has been said, that after the objection was entered pursuant to the court order in Harper v. Levi in 1973, that South Carolina has continued to enforce its plan, rather than coming up with a new reapportionment or submitting to the District Court of the District of Columbia, an action seeking a declared court judgment that the plan is enforceable.","start":46.481,"stop":73.24,"duration":26.76},{"text":"Now, of course, from 1973 until commencement of this suit, the judgment of that District Court was in litigation.","start":73.24,"stop":82.169,"duration":8.93},{"text":"It was appealed by the United States to the Court Of Appeals.","start":82.169,"stop":87.509,"duration":5.34},{"text":"Judge Green in her District Court order specifically said that the order was without prejudice to any right of appeal on the issue, and so we fail to see how that constitutes bad faith or evasion on our part.","start":87.509,"stop":101.391,"duration":13.88},{"text":"We feel also that the record of South Carolina’s compliance with the Voting Rights Act, since its inception should dispel the notion that there is any bad faith or evasion on our part in this case.","start":101.391,"stop":114.087,"duration":12.7},{"text":"We promptly submitted this plan, we mailed it off three days after the Governor signed it in to law, which is, I think is very prompt compliance, in 1972, South Carolina has always complied with the Voting Rights Act.","start":114.087,"stop":128.407,"duration":14.32},{"text":"We are quite proud that we are the only covered jurisdiction and this court has judicially noticed in Perkins v. Matthews that we are the only covered jurisdiction that is rigorously and faithfully complied with the Section 5 pre-clearance provision since the beginning.","start":128.407,"stop":143.832,"duration":15.42},{"text":"We did so in this case, the Attorney General determined that our submission was complete, which we think was his determination to make.","start":143.832,"stop":151.188,"duration":7.36},{"text":"We think, this court clearly said that, in Georgia v. United States, and so we fail to see where the evasion is on our part.","start":151.188,"stop":160.045,"duration":8.86},{"text":"Where is our bad faith?","start":160.045,"stop":163.604,"duration":3.56},{"text":"In fact, we feel that the record indicates the opposite.","start":163.604,"stop":167.041,"duration":3.44},{"text":"Now, the record also shows that the Attorney General did look at our submission.","start":167.041,"stop":173.726,"duration":6.69},{"text":"All of the testimony in the record, all of the evidence in the record points in that direction that nothing to indicate that agency action was withheld which was repeatedly suggested yesterday.","start":173.726,"stop":184.215,"duration":10.49},{"text":"Quite obviously, agency action was not withheld.","start":184.215,"stop":187.391,"duration":3.18},{"text":"The Attorney General received the submission, he reviewed the submission, he reviewed the plan and he acted, it is because he acted, and not because he failed to act, that we have this lawsuit.","start":187.391,"stop":199.486,"duration":12.1},{"text":"The Plaintiffs disagree with that action but it simply is not plausible to claim that he did not look at the plan or did he totally withheld Agency Action, or that he did not review it at all, so that is not the case we are arguing here, it is a case in which the Attorney General did receive the submission.","start":199.486,"stop":220.48,"duration":20.99},{"text":"If there is any question about that I think it is a dispelled by looking at the memorandum he filed with District Court a year later, in which he said, we have again reviewed this submission and we find that our decision there was sound.","start":220.48,"stop":237.9,"duration":17.42},{"text":"That is the same letter in which he went on to say that the plan had a substantial racial effect.","start":237.9,"stop":244.813,"duration":6.91},{"text":"But he starts that memorandum by saying, we have reviewed all of this again, that indicates that he had reviewed it once before and he said we have reached the same conclusion, that that conclusion was sound.","start":244.813,"stop":256.257,"duration":11.44}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That letter is an Appendix here somewhere.","start":256.257,"stop":258.517,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":258.517,"stop":261.026,"duration":2.51},{"text":"You will find that letter is on page in the Appendix starting at Page 51.","start":261.026,"stop":273.559,"duration":12.53},{"text":"I am sorry that is the objection letter.","start":273.559,"stop":275.43,"duration":1.87},{"text":"The memorandum which I am referring is reprinted in the Red Brief in the Appendix there, and you will find that begins on Page 4(a) of that Appendix and the language I am referring to is in the first paragraph of that memorandum.","start":275.43,"stop":294.39,"duration":18.96},{"text":"It says there, \"we have again examined our files to determine whether the conclusion reached, and the reasons for that decision are sound, we conclude again that they were\".","start":294.39,"stop":305.784,"duration":11.39},{"text":"So we think that the record, the facts in this case simply do not support most of the arguments that were being made yesterday in that regard.","start":305.784,"stop":319.693,"duration":13.91},{"text":"It seems to me that to adopt that the position which was urged before the court yesterday, is quite clearly going to create significant problems.","start":319.693,"stop":329.403,"duration":9.71},{"text":"If the court decides to review under the Administrative Procedure Act is permitted, I think yesterday’s argument gave us a good foreshadowing of what is going to happen, we are going to have a host of collateral issues being raised in lawsuits on this matter.","start":329.403,"stop":346.051,"duration":16.65},{"text":"All of these will have to be resolved in future litigation, I do not think those issues are right for adjudication in this court today.","start":346.051,"stop":352.619,"duration":6.57},{"text":"They will have to be resolved, in collateral suits in the future.","start":352.619,"stop":357.643,"duration":5.02},{"text":"Some of the issues that were raised in the questioning yesterday are very difficult issues, who can seek review.","start":357.643,"stop":364.754,"duration":7.11},{"text":"Private parties, the submitting authority, both.","start":364.754,"stop":368.516,"duration":3.76},{"text":"Can private parties seek review of objections as well as non-objections, and I think the difficulty of that question is shown by the fact that the private parties in the United States disagreed on it.","start":368.516,"stop":378.848,"duration":10.33},{"text":"Mr. Wollenberg said, private parties can not.","start":378.848,"stop":381.07,"duration":2.22},{"text":"Mr. Turner said they can if there is some fundamental error that led to the objection.","start":381.07,"stop":388.094,"duration":7.02},{"text":"That is a difficult question which would have to be resolved.","start":388.094,"stop":391.611,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that the Attorney General does not object, or suppose he specifically says that he is not planning to object.","start":391.611,"stop":401.634,"duration":10.02},{"text":"He says he's carefully reviewed the plan and the state statute goes in to effect.","start":401.634,"stop":410.651,"duration":9.02},{"text":"May a private party then bring an independent suit to enjoin the operation of the statute, not on constitutional grounds but on the ground that it does not comply with Section 5?","start":410.651,"stop":425.948,"duration":15.3}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the act itself does not give a clear answer to that, obviously the Act says…","start":425.948,"stop":430.594,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Have there been some decisions, have there been some attempts at private suits to enjoin the...","start":430.594,"stop":437.005,"duration":6.41}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the problem, and I think it is a significant problem; there are certainly reasons why private parties should be allowed in certain circumstances to litigate that issue.","start":437.005,"stop":447.747,"duration":10.74},{"text":"I think the way that has been handled so far and it seems to be something that is acceptable to Congress, but Congress has not changed the Act, it is a liberal rule of intervention, now private parties have intervened...","start":447.747,"stop":461.442,"duration":13.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I know but there is no place to intervene, if the Attorney General does not enter his objection.","start":461.442,"stop":467.939,"duration":6.5}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"You are quite right, because you are speaking of the case in which he says I enter no objection.","start":467.939,"stop":472.618,"duration":4.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I had thought that rule -- I just assumed, I suppose the rule in the statute was that private suits were not permitted.","start":472.618,"stop":485.052,"duration":12.43},{"text":"That after the statute went into effect that private party was remitted to its constitutional remedies.","start":485.052,"stop":491.61,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in the case that you are speaking of, Mr. Justice White --","start":491.61,"stop":495.322,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there some decisions that say that once?","start":495.322,"stop":497.384,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think that the Allen, the Allen decision of this court says precisely that, it says once the state has obtained successful pre-clearance the only remedy parties have is to bring the subsequent contest on the merits.","start":497.384,"stop":510.955,"duration":13.57},{"text":"There is no...","start":510.955,"stop":512.825,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"On what merits?","start":512.825,"stop":514.7,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"On the merits on the plan, that is..","start":514.7,"stop":516.395,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I know, you mean on the constitution.","start":516.395,"stop":517.943,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, on the Constitution.","start":517.943,"stop":519.446,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Assume this statutory standard is more stringent than the constitutional standard, my question really asks may a private party bring a private suit to enforce the statutory standard.","start":519.446,"stop":534.705,"duration":15.26}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think congress has indicated that the constitutional merits are then to be reached.","start":534.705,"stop":540.983,"duration":6.28},{"text":"That the purposes --","start":540.983,"stop":541.881,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they should then be reached but is there some authority for saying that Congress did not intend a private suit such as I described?","start":541.881,"stop":554.208,"duration":12.33}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the language in the Allen case is the best indication of that.","start":554.208,"stop":558.186,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn’t that some argument for suggesting -- isn’t that an argument against allowing review?","start":558.186,"stop":568.777,"duration":10.59}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think quite clearly, it is.","start":568.777,"stop":570.179,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I would suppose you would have made that argument.","start":570.179,"stop":574.224,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if a have not, I hope that I am making it now.","start":574.224,"stop":579.048,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, if Congress did not intend to bar private parties from bringing independent suits to enjoin on the basis of the statutory standard, it would seem odd that it would allow review, at the behest of purely private parties.","start":579.048,"stop":595.695,"duration":16.65}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think if we look at the scheme of Section 5 and see how it relates to the traditional constitutional suit, we begin to get some insight in to that question.","start":595.695,"stop":609.181,"duration":13.49},{"text":"Now, the reason Section 5 was enacted, and I think this is quite clear is because traditional suits were considered not to be an adequate remedy.","start":609.181,"stop":619.384,"duration":10.2},{"text":"But why weren’t they considered to be an adequate remedy, there was a very specific problem that Congress was addressing.","start":619.384,"stop":625.901,"duration":6.52},{"text":"It was a practice which they had seen occur and in some states in the South on a massive basis of undercutting successful Fifteenth Amendment litigation, private parties would have a voting qualification, stricken as unconstitutional they would win their case and the state would react by changing the qualifications, so that there had to be new litigation.","start":625.901,"stop":648.013,"duration":22.11},{"text":"Now pre-clearance and the suspension effect of Section 5 has taken care of that problem.","start":648.013,"stop":654.232,"duration":6.22},{"text":"So that the subsequent contest on the merits, the constitutional contest now is the effective.","start":654.232,"stop":660.02,"duration":5.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on the other hand, if Congress has provided a statutory standard which new voting procedures must conform to.","start":660.02,"stop":676.222,"duration":16.2},{"text":"Why would you argue that congress did not intend a private party to be able to sue on the basis of the statute?","start":676.222,"stop":682.348,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the statute does not say so in so many words?","start":682.348,"stop":684.914,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that one of my difficulties with your question Justice White is that I do not see decision of this court that is yet resolved that question, it is clear that it is a question that has been on your minds.","start":684.914,"stop":697.128,"duration":12.21},{"text":"It seems to me that the court has not yet reached a resolution of that question.","start":697.128,"stop":702.684,"duration":5.56},{"text":"I suppose that had court...","start":702.684,"stop":704.454,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But how about -- have suits been brought in District Courts, have they been dismissed or have they been entertained?","start":704.454,"stop":711.499,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"To my knowledge, no suit has been -- a substantive Section 5 suit has not been brought in a local District Court when the Attorney General has not objected.","start":711.499,"stop":723.62,"duration":12.12},{"text":"Another reason it's hard to cite authorities because this case is one of the first cases in which someone challenged the Attorney General’s non-objection by bringing an action other than the subsequent contest on the merits provided in Section 5, which we think is the remedy that Congress intended to be available and we think it is an adequate remedy today because there would be no undercutting of judgments which was the problem that Section 5 was addressed to in the past.","start":723.62,"stop":756.459,"duration":32.84},{"text":"I think, at the time Congress extended the Act in 1975, there was no decision of this court which would indicate that the substantive standard of Section 5 is clearly different from the Fifteenth Amendment standard.","start":756.459,"stop":774.428,"duration":17.97},{"text":"Some members of the court feel that the standard is the same.","start":774.428,"stop":778.004,"duration":3.58},{"text":"The substantive standard both under the Fifteenth Amendment and under Section 5, and so I do not think Congress was dealing with a situation of which this court has announced a clear rule that substantive Section 5 coverage was different from substantive constitutional coverage.","start":778.004,"stop":795.926,"duration":17.92},{"text":"So that it would have to deal with that issue by amending Section 5 or leaving Section 5 the way it is.","start":795.926,"stop":802.407,"duration":6.48},{"text":"It seems to me that that was the issue in the Beer case which came after the 1975 extension, and as I say, it seems to me from my reading of that case that the court had not made up its mind on the issue yet, and certainly it is a difficult question.","start":802.407,"stop":818.639,"duration":16.23},{"text":"I think our view would be that Congress has resolved that question by saying “Here is the subsequent suit, why would Congress take care to preserve that suit, if it was not because it foresaw exactly the factual situation we have here, private parties disagreeing with the non-objection by the Attorney General\".","start":818.639,"stop":838.797,"duration":20.16},{"text":"It seems to me that’s why Congress was careful to preserve that subsequent contest on the merits.","start":838.797,"stop":846.379,"duration":7.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now when you say substantive contest on the merits, you are talking about the constitution of the suit...","start":846.379,"stop":851.904,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"The subsequent constitutional suit, yes.","start":851.904,"stop":854.413,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but that is not as necessarily as broader remedy.","start":854.413,"stop":860.036,"duration":5.62},{"text":"In other words the plaintiffs might lose that suit and still the Attorney General's objection be sustained in a suit brought by the state challenging it in a Three-Judge District Court here in the District Of Columbia, might it not?","start":860.036,"stop":874.934,"duration":14.9}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true, if the substantive Section 5 standard is in effect only standard, whereas the constitutional requirement is either a purpose or a purpose and effect standard, which language in the decisions in this court would indicate, then there would be a difference.","start":874.934,"stop":892.214,"duration":17.28},{"text":"It seems to me though that the question of purpose and effect is often one in which no bright line can be drawn, and that the Attorney General, if that standard is different clearly could object and if he found a clear discriminatory effect, I think if that standard is different that that would certainly be a possibility for him to object.","start":892.214,"stop":918.928,"duration":26.71},{"text":"I do not think that is the situation we had in this case, in 1972.","start":918.928,"stop":924.903,"duration":5.98},{"text":"There has been some question as to why he differed or what was he doing when he differed in the South Carolina case.","start":924.903,"stop":931.746,"duration":6.84},{"text":"What seems to me that we have to look at the situation in 1972.","start":931.746,"stop":935.188,"duration":3.44},{"text":"I think the reasons are intensely factual in this case.","start":935.188,"stop":939.98,"duration":4.79},{"text":"The Attorney General was faced with the situation in which a previous plan, similar to the plan that is now before the court had been objected to in March of that year.","start":939.98,"stop":953.054,"duration":13.07},{"text":"But the objection was not based on a reasoned decision on the merits.","start":953.054,"stop":959.39,"duration":6.34},{"text":"He said “I can not make up my mind”, therefore under my burden of proof standard in my regulations interpose objection.","start":959.39,"stop":966.738,"duration":7.35},{"text":"He said “we are unable to reach a conclusion”.","start":966.738,"stop":969.224,"duration":2.49},{"text":"That is what he said in March, to Act 932.","start":969.224,"stop":972.582,"duration":3.36},{"text":"Now when he received Act 1205, the plan we are talking about now, in June the situation had changed.","start":972.582,"stop":981.629,"duration":9.05},{"text":"For one thing, constitutional court had found that there was no discriminatory purpose behind that plan and in fact, the plaintiffs in that case had conceded that there was no discriminatory purpose behind the plan.","start":981.629,"stop":997.284,"duration":15.65},{"text":"So, he was dealing with a situation in which parties to that litigation had conceded that there was no discriminatory purpose.","start":997.284,"stop":1004.766,"duration":7.48},{"text":"The court had found no discriminatory purpose.","start":1004.766,"stop":1006.415,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but actually, like out issue here is rather narrow, or you do not really get to the question of the merits of his actions.","start":1006.415,"stop":1017.195,"duration":10.78},{"text":"It is rather the narrow question whether his state of reason for a non-objection was that he was deferred to the action of the Three-Judge Court, wasn’t it?","start":1017.195,"stop":1032.684,"duration":15.49},{"text":"So, there's only the narrow question whether or not much is reviewable, that kind of mistake, if you please, whatever else it is, not for the merits of his -- why he objected or not, isn't that right?","start":1032.684,"stop":1047.134,"duration":14.45}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I quite agree Justice Brennan, but I think..","start":1047.134,"stop":1049.818,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean all the other things that we have been discussing with you so far get above and beyond that -- didn't they.","start":1049.818,"stop":1058.306,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the reasons that he did differ have something to do with whether we consider that difference, unreasonable and I am suggesting that in addition to the fact.","start":1058.306,"stop":1069.249,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I just want to suggest that it is not whether it is reasonable or unreasonable.","start":1069.249,"stop":1073.529,"duration":4.28},{"text":"But it is rather whether, whether that is judicially reviewable, as a matter of law his reliance on that deferral, difference rather, is a reason for not objecting.","start":1073.529,"stop":1086.594,"duration":13.07}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"We do not think that when he differed he was relying only on that court decision, that is the point I am trying to make.","start":1086.594,"stop":1093.578,"duration":6.98},{"text":"We do not think that is the only way.","start":1093.578,"stop":1095.244,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Where did you get that out of the record?","start":1095.244,"stop":1096.762,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay, it seems to me that if we look at his letter, if we look at his letter, and it is in the Appendix.","start":1096.762,"stop":1106.185,"duration":9.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you speaking of the one you referred to before?","start":1106.185,"stop":1108.405,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that was the memorandum he filed in the District of Columbia court.","start":1108.405,"stop":1112.282,"duration":3.88},{"text":"But if we look at his 1972 letter, which he said he was referring, and I am referring to Page 48 of the handbook (ph), the Appendix, and if I might invite the attention of the court to the full paragraph which is at the bottom half of that page.","start":1112.282,"stop":1134.393,"duration":22.11},{"text":"He first says, “we think that our function is to do what the District Court of the District of Columbia would do”.","start":1134.393,"stop":1144.06,"duration":9.67},{"text":"“If this case were presented to them in a declaratory judgment action”, that is the first thing he says.","start":1144.06,"stop":1149.261,"duration":5.2},{"text":"The second thing he says is “under this standard that is under the standard of doing what we think the District Court would do, we feel constrained to differ to the judgment”.","start":1149.261,"stop":1162.144,"duration":12.88},{"text":"Then he goes on and explains that a little bit more, it seems to me that he indicates other factors besides just the fact that that judgment had been entered in the constitutional case.","start":1162.144,"stop":1173.331,"duration":11.19},{"text":"He says also that there is a right of appeal to the Supreme Court.","start":1173.331,"stop":1181.813,"duration":8.48},{"text":"Parties who feel aggrieved have a full right to seek appellate review, he also notes in the previous paragraph that he is considering this under a request for expedited consideration because the elections are getting near.","start":1181.813,"stop":1196.751,"duration":14.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course, in fact there was no, at this state, there was no determination of the District of Columbia in a Three-Judge Court...","start":1196.751,"stop":1204.582,"duration":7.83}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was not.","start":1204.582,"stop":1206.271,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So the question really is when he says “under this standard” may he do what he did, defer the determination of the Three-Judge District Court in South Carolina, merely because he thinks what they did might have been what the District of Columbia's Three-Judge Court would do.","start":1206.271,"stop":1226.72,"duration":20.45},{"text":"Isn’t that what the issue is?","start":1226.72,"stop":1227.797,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes but we think that issue is reviewable.","start":1227.797,"stop":1231.804,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the preliminary issue.","start":1231.804,"stop":1234.745,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but to that extent is reviewable, his reliance on that reason for non-objection?","start":1234.745,"stop":1241.389,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, I think that what he was saying..","start":1241.389,"stop":1243.843,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but isn’t that the only question we have to decide in this case?","start":1243.843,"stop":1247.084,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that all that you have to decide is that Section 5 means what it says when it says that if the..","start":1247.084,"stop":1252.094,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, please do not put it that way.","start":1252.094,"stop":1254.13,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay, I am sorry.","start":1254.13,"stop":1254.275,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn’t that the issue for us to decide whether or not his non-objection based on that ground is judicially reviewable?","start":1254.275,"stop":1261.98,"duration":7.7}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think yes it is, quite clearly.","start":1261.98,"stop":1264.329,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"At your submission that, even though this can be defended as more or less reasonable at least at the time that it was made in the light of the -- then State of the law.","start":1264.329,"stop":1275.184,"duration":10.86},{"text":"I thought it was your position that even he had said “we are opposing no objection because of South Carolina voted republican at the last election”.","start":1275.184,"stop":1284.651,"duration":9.47},{"text":"Even that would not be reviewable.","start":1284.651,"stop":1288.253,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We think that your position at...","start":1288.253,"stop":1291.901,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"If that were his objection we would be quite confident in coming to the District Court of the District of Columbia ourselves if he objected on that basis.","start":1291.901,"stop":1299.064,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I said, he didn’t object, he says, we are interposing no objection because your state voted right at the last election.","start":1299.064,"stop":1306.59,"duration":7.53},{"text":"What if he did that, would that be reviewable?","start":1306.59,"stop":1309.997,"duration":3.41},{"text":"In your submission it would not be isn’t it that correct?","start":1309.997,"stop":1312.665,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"It would not fall within the kind of review being sought here.","start":1312.665,"stop":1318.436,"duration":5.77},{"text":"I do not think we would want to go so far as to say that what..","start":1318.436,"stop":1322.63,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Even if it does go, and necessarily goes that far as I understand it, and I do not find that shocking.","start":1322.63,"stop":1329.296,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"We think that Congress intended to preclude that kind of review.","start":1329.296,"stop":1332.933,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, that is your submission.","start":1332.933,"stop":1334.387,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and we think that if the Attorney General ever were to do that Justice Stewart, that the remedy for that is clear.","start":1334.387,"stop":1342.298,"duration":7.91},{"text":"What happened in 1971, Congressional oversight, now if..","start":1342.298,"stop":1346.218,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the reason they put the onus on the Attorney General.","start":1346.218,"stop":1348.935,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1348.935,"stop":1350.192,"duration":1.26},{"text":"Now before 1971 it is quite clear from all of the evidence in the Congressional hearings that the Attorney General was not reviewing many of these submissions.","start":1350.192,"stop":1359.999,"duration":9.81},{"text":"Mr. Turner said and it's their position, we were too busy with voting examiners and registrars down in Mississippi to pay much attention to pre-clearance and it is also clear that in many cases he never responded hundreds of cases.","start":1359.999,"stop":1374.775,"duration":14.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose then you would day that his non-objection would not be reviewable even if he just says we are not interposing an objection because we have not had time to look at it.","start":1374.775,"stop":1388.551,"duration":13.78}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1388.551,"stop":1389.665,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We are just not able to do the job that the statute contemplates.","start":1389.665,"stop":1393.427,"duration":3.76},{"text":"Would you say, non- review?","start":1393.427,"stop":1394.839,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Non-review in that case.","start":1394.839,"stop":1395.922,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you must say that because it sounds to me like that is precisely what happened -- in effect what happened here because he never, never looked at it in the light of the Section 5 standard.","start":1395.922,"stop":1406.934,"duration":11.01},{"text":"He simply said “some courts decided it is constitutional”.","start":1406.934,"stop":1412.019,"duration":5.09},{"text":"So it is just the same as saying, “I have never looked at it from the stand point of Section 5”.","start":1412.019,"stop":1417.396,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"We think that proposition is not as shocking as it seems on its face because there is congressional oversight.","start":1417.396,"stop":1422.122,"duration":4.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That seems to me...","start":1422.122,"stop":1424.356,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":1424.356,"stop":1425.124,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no it isn’t that shocking, it's true.","start":1425.124,"stop":1428.134,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"And it seems to me that in Georgia, in the Georgia case this court said that these things are things that are left with the Attorney General.","start":1428.134,"stop":1436.546,"duration":8.41},{"text":"We do not have to find that what he did do is the only thing he could do or...","start":1436.546,"stop":1441.782,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Or even the right thing.","start":1441.782,"stop":1443.553,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Or even the right thing.","start":1443.553,"stop":1445.543,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He might have been egregiously wrong but I thought it was your argument that it is simply not reviewable.","start":1445.543,"stop":1449.557,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"That is our argument.","start":1449.557,"stop":1451.178,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I would not back away from it, if I were you.","start":1451.178,"stop":1453.059,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"And it seems to me that if the Attorney General ever begins flagrantly abusing that power or doing something which was clearly, what Congress felt that it did not want, Congressional oversight would be the remedy for that case, and not—Yes.","start":1453.059,"stop":1471.859,"duration":18.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Copy or oversight, if you…","start":1471.859,"stop":1473.416,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, of course that hypothesis is completely implausible because the act has been very successful in accomplishing its purpose.","start":1473.416,"stop":1482.948,"duration":9.53},{"text":"Even in all those years that the Attorney General was not reviewing every submission, Blacks were making great strides forward in the South.","start":1482.948,"stop":1490.682,"duration":7.73},{"text":"Mr. Pottinger(ph) and others have said in the testimony in 1975, “this is the most successful piece of civil rights legislation ever passed by Congress and so to talk about this hypothesis, I think is implausible as a matter of experience, but even in those situations, Congressional oversight is available and as you suggest it is just public outrage, that kind of behavior, if it occurred certainly..","start":1490.682,"stop":1516.699,"duration":26.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bell, think hypothetically, please.","start":1516.699,"stop":1520.494,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The Attorney General says, “I am constrained to pass this up because the federal Court has decided to question”.","start":1520.494,"stop":1530.569,"duration":10.08},{"text":"And he sends that letter and two days later, he sends a letter and says I was mistaken in that, and I do now object.","start":1530.569,"stop":1539.493,"duration":8.92}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Under his guidelines, if he does both of those things within the 60 day period, the objection will stand, Justice Marshall, and the state could not enforce.","start":1539.493,"stop":1548.506,"duration":9.01},{"text":"I think that is clear in his guidelines.","start":1548.506,"stop":1549.405,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The trouble is you did not do it within 60 days.","start":1549.405,"stop":1552.388,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Here, 434 days later he entered an objection pursuant to court order.","start":1552.388,"stop":1557.278,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"So, he says because he did not do it within 60 days.","start":1557.278,"stop":1560.819,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely and we think that is what Congress has said and what this court said in Allen.","start":1560.819,"stop":1568.033,"duration":7.21},{"text":"Congress knew that the Attorney General did not make a reasoned decision on the merits in 1975 and they did not change the act.","start":1568.033,"stop":1577.049,"duration":9.02},{"text":"Mr. Turner suggested yesterday that they or I understood him to suggest that they always give reasons, when they make a response but his guidelines say that they do not.","start":1577.049,"stop":1586.284,"duration":9.24},{"text":"If he fails to object or says no objection 51.20 of the guidelines say nothing about him giving reasons.","start":1586.284,"stop":1593.35,"duration":7.07},{"text":"If he objects, under the section dealing with notification of decision to object, it says that sub (a) that he will give reasons there and Congress knew that the interpretation of Section 5 was that he does not have to give reasons, he does not have to act.","start":1593.35,"stop":1611.064,"duration":17.71},{"text":"There's language of this court in the City of Richmond case, which indicates that, and the proponents placed that interpretation on it in 1975, Congress knew that’s what people thought it meant and Congress did not change the language of the section.","start":1611.064,"stop":1629.749,"duration":18.68},{"text":"I do think, to return to a point that I was addressing earlier that all kinds of questions will be raised if this sort of litigation is opened up, not just question of who can seek review, but the question of whether venue is in the District of Columbia or in local courts.","start":1629.749,"stop":1650.163,"duration":20.41},{"text":"Whether 14(b) of the Act is a limit on the general venue provisions of the APA, indeed whether 14(b) requires a Three-Judge Court in an APA determination, since Three-Judge Courts are required elsewhere.","start":1650.163,"stop":1665.836,"duration":15.67},{"text":"Of course, there was not a three judge court in Harper v. Levi.","start":1665.836,"stop":1669.068,"duration":3.23},{"text":"How soon must review be sought?","start":1669.068,"stop":1671.102,"duration":2.03},{"text":"There was great emphasis placed on the timeliness of the Harper V. Levi suit, in this case, but what happens if people wait a few months longer?","start":1671.102,"stop":1679.329,"duration":8.23},{"text":"All of these are collateral questions that I think would be an enormous waste of judicial time.","start":1679.329,"stop":1686.827,"duration":7.5},{"text":"Why not go to the remedies Congress has provided which get to the merits of these plans?","start":1686.827,"stop":1691.944,"duration":5.12},{"text":"Either the subsequent contest by parties or the declaratory judgment action by the state.","start":1691.944,"stop":1700.37,"duration":8.43},{"text":"If I may, I would like to address myself also to the question of special elections in 1978, and just briefly of course, we think the issue is entirely hypothetical because the District Court was correct in its decision.","start":1700.37,"stop":1715.218,"duration":14.85},{"text":"We would note very quickly that under the Attorney General’s guidelines were these objections ultimately to be sustained, we could go before him and ask him to withdraw it if the facts of the law have changed.","start":1715.218,"stop":1727.333,"duration":12.12},{"text":"We believe that they have in this case and we would want to see that and also everyone admits that we have the right to come in to the District of Columbia court and seek the declaratory judgment.","start":1727.333,"stop":1740.006,"duration":12.67},{"text":"We would like that option left open.","start":1740.006,"stop":1740.949,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The state, yes that is right.","start":1740.949,"stop":1742.063,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"The state, yes the Senate.","start":1742.063,"stop":1745.204,"duration":3.14},{"text":"We note that in Mississippi and Georgia, legislators have been allowed to serve out their full terms even after objections have been entered, or plans have been struck down as constitutional and we believe that good faith of our senate entitles it to that consideration as well.","start":1745.204,"stop":1762.846,"duration":17.64},{"text":"As I say, we do basically consider that to be hypothetical, of course, our position is that the judgment of the District Court should be affirmed.","start":1762.846,"stop":1772.771,"duration":9.92},{"text":"South Carolina promptly submitted its plan in 1972 in full compliance with the Voting Rights Act.","start":1772.771,"stop":1779.229,"duration":6.46},{"text":"There was nothing else we could have done to comply more fully.","start":1779.229,"stop":1782.799,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The Attorney General did not object within 60 days.","start":1782.799,"stop":1786.282,"duration":3.48},{"text":"Section 5 says that when that happens the state is entitled to enforce the plan.","start":1786.282,"stop":1793.629,"duration":7.35},{"text":"On these facts, we ask this court to hold that South Carolina may enforce its plan.","start":1793.629,"stop":1799.177,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Because congress said what it meant in Section 5, and Section 5 means exactly what it says, that we can enforce.","start":1799.177,"stop":1806.83,"duration":7.65},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1806.83,"stop":1812.199,"duration":5.37}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wallenberg, you have about three minutes left.","start":1812.199,"stop":1816.088,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"If the court please, I do not find it reassuring that Professor Bell says that great strides are being made under the Voting Rights Act, because great strides are not being made with respect to the South Carolina senate which remains all white, all of the Attorney General and the memorandum that Professor Bell keeps referring to that is in Appendix (a) in Red Brief.","start":1816.088,"stop":1843.329,"duration":27.24},{"text":"In that memorandum, the Attorney General found that with proper districts it would be assumed that if there were racial voting that blacks could elect four or five members of the state senate, and maybe progress elsewhere in the country, in Georgia and in Mississippi and indeed in the South Carolina House as a result of orders of this court or objections of the Attorney General, progress has been made.","start":1843.329,"stop":1867.871,"duration":24.54},{"text":"We are here to try to get progress in the state senate of South Carolina.","start":1867.871,"stop":1872.051,"duration":4.18},{"text":"Much has been said about the 1975 re-enactment by Congress of the act and it must have been accepting 60 day limit and everything for which Professor Bell has been arguing.","start":1872.051,"stop":1882.811,"duration":10.76},{"text":"Professor Bell overlooks the language in the house that is set forth in Footnote 42 of his brief at Page 29 where Mr. Representative Edwards, expressed great approval for the Harper and Levi decision which has just been decided when Congress was re-enacting in 1975.","start":1882.811,"stop":1910.447,"duration":27.64},{"text":"And we have to say I think that Congress in that re-enactment was thoroughly aware of Harper v. Levi and I want to refer the court also to the Senate Report number 94-95 in 94th Congress, first Session, Page 18, where a reference also was made to what was then to the reference to Harper v. Kleindienst, and Connor v. Waller.","start":1910.447,"stop":1941.645,"duration":31.2},{"text":"So Congress in 1975, I think, was well aware of the fact that if Attorney General went completely out of the statutory scheme and abdicated his function that some result would be reached.","start":1941.645,"stop":1954.854,"duration":13.21},{"text":"A lot of concern has been expressed.","start":1954.854,"stop":1956.257,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The statutory scheme is simply for him to interpose an objection or not to interpose an objection, that is all the statute talks about.","start":1956.257,"stop":1963.544,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, but it is settled under his own regulations and this court's decision in Georgia, that that is to be a considered decision like a court would reach, and it is not a decision --","start":1963.544,"stop":1976.565,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That his regulations were permissible, that is what the Georgia case, and I wrote the opinion.","start":1976.565,"stop":1983.623,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Sir, I think that the kind of determination that the Attorney General is intended to make under Section 5 is the kind of determination that the Attorney General, that would be made by the District of Columbia court if the case were presented to it.","start":1983.623,"stop":2002.949,"duration":19.33},{"text":"And this court in the Thermtron case and in Dunlop v. Bachowski has made very clear that where an agency goes entirely outside of its statutory function that this court will fashion a remedy without upsetting the statutory scheme.","start":2002.949,"stop":2021.916,"duration":18.97},{"text":"A limited and narrow remedy and we are asking in this case only the most narrow and limited remedy which was applied in Harper v. Levi which was an order to the Attorney General not to reach a particular result but in order to perform his function and to reach a decision that was independent, and that is what he did and it was a decision that was entirely negative to the statute and he indicated that it has been his view for at least a year, that the statute was an improper statute.","start":2021.916,"stop":2048.275,"duration":26.36}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wallenberg, will you pin point a little more clearly for me.","start":2048.275,"stop":2052.701,"duration":4.43},{"text":"In what perspective did the Attorney General go outside of the statutory authority?","start":2052.701,"stop":2060.391,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor when the Attorney General..","start":2060.391,"stop":2064.819,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"As Mr. Justice Stewart suggested the statute gives him certain options; he took one of them, didn’t he...","start":2064.819,"stop":2073.862,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"In failing to object, he took an option. But just like the District Court in the Thermtron case which remanded a removed case on a ground that was not authorized in the statute.","start":2073.862,"stop":2093.58,"duration":19.72},{"text":"In that same and was mandamus for that despite statutory language and history of non review of remand decisions.","start":2093.58,"stop":2101.812,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Just like that decision in Thermtron, the case here was that the Attorney General putting aside his own views as to validity of the statute, feeling that he was compelled, constrained, to follow a District Court judgment which was not on the Voting Rights Act which was on the Fifteenth Amendment and where the burden of proof had been on the plaintiffs.","start":2101.812,"stop":2128.309,"duration":26.5},{"text":"And where the District court had disclaimed, that it was passing on Section 5 recognizing that that was a function for the D.C. courts or the Attorney General. He felt constrained to follow that.","start":2128.309,"stop":2141.387,"duration":13.08},{"text":"I cannot think of a clearer case of well intentions and good faith, no doubt, but a clearer case of abdication of his clear function under Section 5 to make a judgment under the standards of the Voting Rights Act.","start":2141.387,"stop":2157.045,"duration":15.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When you called it an abdication, would you also agree, I take it you would agree, that he made an error of law.","start":2157.045,"stop":2165.818,"duration":8.77}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"It was an error of law, Your Honor but it was an error of law of kind and degree that goes far beyond an ordinary review on the merits where factual questions are taken into account and statutory policy.","start":2165.818,"stop":2181.221,"duration":15.4},{"text":"In other words anything can be called error of law but when the Attorney General says “I won’t exercise my own judgment because I can’t, and I can’t exercise my own judgment because the District Court reached a conclusion under the Fifteenth Amendment while disclaiming the Voting Rights Act”.","start":2181.221,"stop":2197.409,"duration":16.19},{"text":"Under those circumstances I say, like in the Thermtron case he has abdicated his function.","start":2197.409,"stop":2202.972,"duration":5.56},{"text":"And like Dunlop v. Bachowski, I think that this court can fashion a remedy which will not open up the chamber of horrors that have been suggested to Your Honors.","start":2202.972,"stop":2214.563,"duration":11.59},{"text":"Not open up general review, everyone coming in to attack the Attorney General, but after all the purpose of Section 5, was basically to place the burden on the covered states to demonstrate that their changes of electoral procedures were proper under the standards of the Voting Rights Act and if the Attorney General in passing on that didn’t apply the standards of the Voting Rights Act, but applied a standard of a District court on the constitution, it seems to me that it is legitimate to call that an abdication of function.","start":2214.563,"stop":2251.405,"duration":36.84}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you gentlemen.","start":2251.405,"stop":2252.395,"duration":0.99},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2252.395,"stop":2254.289,"duration":1.89}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 18, 1977","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/17267","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear arguments next in 75-1583, Morris & Woods against Gressette.","start":0,"stop":63.174,"duration":63.17},{"text":"Mr. Wollenberg.","start":63.174,"stop":63.954,"duration":0.78},{"text":"I think you may proceed.","start":63.954,"stop":65.961,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the court.","start":65.961,"stop":70.39,"duration":4.43},{"text":"This case has spawned procedural complexities but what is at stake here is not at all complex.","start":70.39,"stop":79.05,"duration":8.66},{"text":"Nearly four years ago, the Attorney General of the United States, objected under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act to South Carolina Act 1205, a 1972 enactment reapportioning the South Carolina State Senate.","start":79.05,"stop":100.232,"duration":21.18},{"text":"That enactment included three aspects which have been hallmarks of discriminatory effect namely, multimember districts, numbered seats, and a majority runoff requirement.","start":100.232,"stop":116.182,"duration":15.95},{"text":"The Attorney General found that Act Number 1205 has a clear and substantial racial effect.","start":116.182,"stop":129.369,"duration":13.19},{"text":"Following the Attorney General’s objection, South Carolina never availed itself of the alternate pre-clearance procedure open to it under Section 5, namely, a declaratory action before a District Court in the District of Columbia.","start":129.369,"stop":151.26,"duration":21.89},{"text":"Instead, the state has simply continued to give effect to Act 1205 without Section 5 clearance and it is that situation for which we seek regress here.","start":151.26,"stop":166.963,"duration":15.7},{"text":"The court below having refused our request for injunctive relief against continued enforcement of the statute.","start":166.963,"stop":177.72,"duration":10.76},{"text":"Basically, as we see it, we seek compliance by South Carolina with the Voting Rights Act.","start":177.72,"stop":185.211,"duration":7.49},{"text":"Compliance which has generally been forthcoming in covered state.","start":185.211,"stop":189.899,"duration":4.69},{"text":"Indeed South Carolina itself complied with the Voting Rights Act in responding to an objection by the Attorney General to its House of Representatives apportionment plan and it enacted a new plan which ultimately met with approval.","start":189.899,"stop":214.186,"duration":24.29},{"text":"So that today the South Carolina House is apportioned in accordance with the law and today in the South Carolina House, there are a number of black members.","start":214.186,"stop":227.476,"duration":13.29},{"text":"Today in the South Carolina Senate, there are no black members.","start":227.476,"stop":233.105,"duration":5.63},{"text":"And the situation which I have described came about as a result of an error, a legal error of the Attorney General of the United States in 1972.","start":233.105,"stop":245.066,"duration":11.96},{"text":"He first declined to object to Act 1205 not because he thought the Act was valid but because he thought he was compelled to defer to a District Court judgment in South Carolina sustaining the constitutionality of Act 1205 but disclaiming any intention to pass on the validity of the act under the Voting Rights Act.","start":245.066,"stop":276.459,"duration":31.39},{"text":"Now, I have referred rather flatly to this ruling of the Attorney General as an error.","start":276.459,"stop":282.477,"duration":6.02},{"text":"I do so because it was determined to be an error in Harper against Levi because the United States has conceded the error both in this court and in the court below.","start":282.477,"stop":295.703,"duration":13.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That determination is not binding on us I suppose, is it?","start":295.703,"stop":299.067,"duration":3.36},{"text":"South Carolina was not a party to the litigation in that case.","start":299.067,"stop":302.574,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"You are speaking of Harper v. Levi.","start":302.574,"stop":304.051,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":304.051,"stop":306.077,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The determination of Harper v. Levi is not binding on this court, Your Honor, but we do suggest, in addition to arguing that the Harper v. Levi hearing was correct in determining that the limited reviewability that took place here was proper.","start":306.077,"stop":328.753,"duration":22.68},{"text":"We also argue as an alternate ground that the Harper v. Levi court having jurisdiction to enter the interlocutory orders that it issued and the Attorney General’s time to object having been told under those interlocutory orders, the objection of the Attorney General was a valid act and if it ultimately would determine that Harper v. Levi reached a wrong result, this would simply free the Attorney General to withdraw his objection but would not nullify his objection not full time on the grounds of --.","start":328.753,"stop":365.745,"duration":36.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say the Attorney General’s time to object was told by the court orders, actually the court orders themselves were issued after the expiration of the 60-day period, were they not?","start":365.745,"stop":380.088,"duration":14.34},{"text":"Can you answer that yes or no?","start":380.088,"stop":382.323,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I can answer that, it is our position that they were not entered after the expiration of the 60-day period.","start":382.323,"stop":389.219,"duration":6.9},{"text":"It was the finding of the District Court in the District of Columbia that they were not entered after the expiration period.","start":389.219,"stop":396.748,"duration":7.53},{"text":"Now, I am speaking now of the preliminary order that was entered by the District Court that extended the Attorney General’s power.","start":396.748,"stop":405.355,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn’t it a fact that that order itself was entered after the expiration of 60 days, following a submission of South Carolina’s plan?","start":405.355,"stop":416.379,"duration":11.02}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it is our position that it was not entered after the 60 days effectively began to run.","start":416.379,"stop":424.717,"duration":8.34},{"text":"You will remember that this court held in the Georgia case, that the Attorney General’s regulations extending the beginning of the 60-day period until he had complete information on the submission before him was a valid exercise of authority on his part.","start":424.717,"stop":443.302,"duration":18.59},{"text":"It was our contention in Harper which was agreed to by the District Court that the Attorney General’s time for acting had been extended by him in connection with requesting additional submissions up to June 19th, 1972 so that when we went before the District Court on August 10, 1972, the 60 days had not expired.","start":443.302,"stop":469.605,"duration":26.3},{"text":"We believe, if Your Honor please, that that whole 60-day question is immaterial to the issues that are before this court.","start":469.605,"stop":477.015,"duration":7.41},{"text":"But I --","start":477.015,"stop":477.556,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What if you wrong on that -- if you say it is immaterial, you must mean that even if you are wrong on that and the Attorney General’s 60-day period had expired before there was ever any court order, you can nonetheless (Inaudible), is that right?","start":477.556,"stop":492.376,"duration":14.82}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely, Your Honor.","start":492.376,"stop":500.27,"duration":7.89},{"text":"I was saying why the Attorney General’s action was an error and I had mentioned it was held to be an error in Harper against Levi and that the United States has now conceded both in the court below and in this court that it was an error.","start":500.27,"stop":516.919,"duration":16.65},{"text":"I also add that this court’s controlling subsequent decisions in Connor v. Waller and most recently in United States against Board of Supervisors of Warren County established, we think, that if anything, the deferral should have gone in the other direction.","start":516.919,"stop":533.773,"duration":16.85},{"text":"In other words, the District Court in South Carolina should not have been passing on the constitutional issue until the Attorney General has passed on the Section 5 of the Voting Rights issue.","start":533.773,"stop":544.263,"duration":10.49},{"text":"Now the court below never reached this question.","start":544.263,"stop":546.544,"duration":2.28},{"text":"The court below found that the Attorney General’s ruling on Act 1205 was improperly reviewed in Harper against Levi and on that premise it treated the Attorney General’s definitive objection to the statute as a nullity.","start":546.544,"stop":562.382,"duration":15.84},{"text":"I think the parties here including the United States, which is here as amicus, are in agreement that the central issue here is whether the Attorney General’s initial determination --.","start":562.382,"stop":575.189,"duration":12.81}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wollenberg, can I interrupt you for just a second?","start":575.189,"stop":577.315,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Does the full text of the letter of June 30, 1972 appear in the papers before us anywhere?","start":577.315,"stop":584.209,"duration":6.89},{"text":"I know it is referred to as Exhibit 5 to the complaint but that wasn’t reprinted.","start":584.209,"stop":587.842,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"It appears on Page Appendix 47 Mr. Justice Stevens.","start":587.842,"stop":595.949,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":595.949,"stop":598.549,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"As I was indicating, the central issue here is reviewability.","start":598.549,"stop":604.186,"duration":5.64},{"text":"If the limited reviewability that we are talking about here which is not reviewability on the merits, is not review of whether the Attorney General should have found the act to be objectionable or not but only review of his legal statement that he was compelled not to enter his own independent judgment.","start":604.186,"stop":626.786,"duration":22.6},{"text":"If it was reviewable as we contend, the United States agrees and as Harper and Levi squarely held, then we submit the sole basis of the decision below is destroyed.","start":626.786,"stop":637.744,"duration":10.96},{"text":"I turn now to the limited reviewability issue.","start":637.744,"stop":640.839,"duration":3.1},{"text":"Mr. Justice Rehnquist, with reference to your earlier question, the reason that we regard the 60 days as immaterial to the present case is that it is established law, we think, under the Administrative Procedure Act under this court's decision in Dunlop that and the International Harvester case which we have quoted and cited in our brief that “where there is judicial review, the statutory period which is created and imposed on an administrative agency for its action is not governing the court in engaging judicial review.”","start":640.839,"stop":687.408,"duration":46.57},{"text":"The present case is a perfect example of why that has to be necessary.","start":687.408,"stop":690.84,"duration":3.43},{"text":"If the Attorney General remains silent until 11 o’clock on the night of the 60th day, there would hardly be time for a judicial review.","start":690.84,"stop":702.249,"duration":11.41},{"text":"If there is judicial review, then the courts have uniformly held that the power exists within a reasonable time after the agency has committed the action complained of.","start":702.249,"stop":714.585,"duration":12.34},{"text":"In this case, there can be no question of laches, obviously, the case was brought very quickly either just before the expiration of the 60 days, Mr. Justice Rehnquist or immediately after depending on how you calculate the 60 days.","start":714.585,"stop":729.316,"duration":14.73},{"text":"In either event, it was brought in a timely fashion.","start":729.316,"stop":733.474,"duration":4.16},{"text":"The reviewability, we think, is essentially un-debatable.","start":733.474,"stop":739.845,"duration":6.37},{"text":"The Administrative Procedure Act was designed to fill the interstices in statutes which created review but which for some reason did not create review complete enough to deal with a critical situation.","start":739.845,"stop":756.663,"duration":16.82},{"text":"And as the court is well aware, there are three well established exceptions stated in the Administrative Procedure Act and none of them applies here.","start":756.663,"stop":766.308,"duration":9.64},{"text":"One of them is where Congress, in so many words, has precluded judicial review.","start":766.308,"stop":772.106,"duration":5.8},{"text":"Congress has simply said of this particular action there will be no judicial review.","start":772.106,"stop":777.576,"duration":5.47},{"text":"Congress knows exactly how to do that and that Congress remembered how to do it in this case, is established clearly by the fact that it used that kind of language in Section 4 but did not use it in Section 5.","start":777.576,"stop":789.962,"duration":12.39},{"text":"A second major area of exception is where the matter is committed to agency discretion.","start":789.962,"stop":801.893,"duration":11.93},{"text":"The action here of the Attorney General is not in any sense committed to agency discretion.","start":801.893,"stop":809.696,"duration":7.8},{"text":"The Attorney General’s own regulations recognized that he acts in a quasi-judicial capacity that he is in effect acting to pass on a submission of a covered state in lieu, if he finds affirmatively, in lieu of the Three-Judge Court.","start":809.696,"stop":828.065,"duration":18.37},{"text":"His own regulations state that he will apply the same standards that the court does and this court reviewed his activities in that regard, in the Georgia case and made clear its view that the Attorney General does not act on a discretionary basis.","start":828.065,"stop":843.68,"duration":15.61},{"text":"Finally, there is the recognition even by the appellees that it is well settled.","start":843.68,"stop":855.549,"duration":11.87},{"text":"I am referring to their Note 68 in their brief at Pages 37 and 38 where appellees say that the courts may determine whether an official is acting beyond the scope of his statutory authority, even in those cases where they can not review the manner in which he exercises his authority.","start":855.549,"stop":875.88,"duration":20.33},{"text":"And that, we suggest is what occurred here in substance.","start":875.88,"stop":881.598,"duration":5.72},{"text":"So in some then on the reviewability question, we submit that it is clear that Congress did not preclude judicial review. It is clear that the action involved was not committed through agency discretion.","start":881.598,"stop":902.916,"duration":21.32},{"text":"And finally, we think it is clear that there is not an adequate remedy at law.","start":902.916,"stop":907.616,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Appelles --","start":907.616,"stop":907.906,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wallenberg, may I give you a hypothetical that has been troubling me, as I think about this case?","start":907.906,"stop":913.49,"duration":5.58},{"text":"Supposing the Attorney General after 30 days at run, wrote a letter saying “my office is terribly busy.","start":913.49,"stop":919.618,"duration":6.13},{"text":"These are awfully complicated matters.","start":919.618,"stop":921.291,"duration":1.67},{"text":"I don’t have a big enough staff to handle them intelligently therefore I will not issue a letter.”","start":921.291,"stop":927.278,"duration":5.99},{"text":"Could that be reviewed?","start":927.278,"stop":929.571,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe, Mr. Justice Stevens, that that issue was considered in the Evers case that the District Court held that a failure to object on the ground that he was not ready to decide whether to object was not a valid ground that it was reviewable.","start":929.571,"stop":948.615,"duration":19.04},{"text":"That this court never, as a court, never reached the issue because the appeal was dismissed for failure to perfect in time or I believe --","start":948.615,"stop":957.797,"duration":9.18}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"If that kind of a disposition would be reviewable would not that be a way in which he could get additional time to make such an announcement to have somebody bring a suit saying you should not do it on that basis, then you would have all the time in the world to study the matter, wouldn’t he?","start":957.797,"stop":972.551,"duration":14.75}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"If, Your Honor please, I think that this court upholding in Georgia, the Attorney General extending his own time beyond the 60 days literally stated in the statute in order to get the full information he needs already is a somewhat of an “open sesame” for him to extend a little.","start":972.551,"stop":987.207,"duration":14.66}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":987.207,"stop":987.986,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"But I think basically, if you consider the purpose of this provision for Attorney General Approval its provision for approval of a routine statutes that do not raise serious questions, the state always has the opportunity to go to the Three-Judge District Court in the District of Columbia.","start":987.986,"stop":1005.767,"duration":17.78},{"text":"So that if the Attorney General for some reason is not prepared to act promptly, the state always has the alternative remedy.","start":1005.767,"stop":1013.368,"duration":7.6},{"text":"And there is no suggestion, I think, that the Attorney General ever has, or ever would have used that point.","start":1013.368,"stop":1018.941,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The Attorney General is always free to simply say on the 60th day, I object because your plan does not quite convince me and has he asked for more information.","start":1018.941,"stop":1030.623,"duration":11.68}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that to be true, Your Honor.","start":1030.623,"stop":1032.388,"duration":1.76},{"text":"I think that the particular formulation in Evers suggested that he was not making the decision one way or the other on the merits which the District Court in Evers thought he should have made.","start":1032.388,"stop":1046.477,"duration":14.09},{"text":"I was addressing the adequacy of the remedy of law or the adequacy of other remedies.","start":1046.477,"stop":1054.067,"duration":7.59},{"text":"The appellees and to some degree the court below, have made a great deal of the notion that really not having the Attorney General perform his function really does not damage anyone because Section 5 has preserved the rights of plaintiffs to go to Three-Judge Districts courts in the state and pursue the matter under the Fifteenth Amendment.","start":1054.067,"stop":1074.371,"duration":20.3},{"text":"So the fact that the Attorney General has cleared the statute, really does not hurt anyone and these other remedies are adequate.","start":1074.371,"stop":1081.733,"duration":7.36},{"text":"The short answer to that, we believe to be a given rather eloquently in the Amicus brief for the United States in this court which we respectfully adopt in that respect.","start":1081.733,"stop":1093.327,"duration":11.59},{"text":"And I would say here only that this kind of a defense or this kind of an argument flies in the face of the whole philosophy of the Voting Rights Act, which is adopted by Congress and upheld by this Court in South Carolina against Katzenbach.","start":1093.327,"stop":1110.059,"duration":16.73},{"text":"The Congress of the United States did not think that the Fifteenth Amendment remedies that existed before that and still exist and were preserved in the act were adequate.","start":1110.059,"stop":1119.648,"duration":9.59},{"text":"That is why the Voting Rights Act.","start":1119.648,"stop":1120.989,"duration":1.34},{"text":"The Voting Rights Act placed the burden on covered states, required them to show that their new proposed legislation would not be discriminatory in purpose or effect and gave them an opportunity of getting that clearance either in the District of Columbia Court or with the Attorney General.","start":1120.989,"stop":1138.156,"duration":17.17},{"text":"If they can get it with the Attorney General without his performing his duty then we submit that that destroys basically renders nugatory, the whole essential structure of the Voting Rights Act.","start":1138.156,"stop":1151.826,"duration":13.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would the plaintiffs in this case have been limited in venue to the District Court to the District of Columbia or could they have brought suit anywhere?","start":1151.826,"stop":1161.03,"duration":9.2}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The plaintiffs in Harper?","start":1161.03,"stop":1163.027,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In Harper, yes.","start":1163.027,"stop":1165.091,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it is arguable and persuasively so on the basis of legislative history as the government has indicated in its brief, amicus in this court.","start":1165.091,"stop":1177.181,"duration":12.09},{"text":"That under the language of Section 14(b) of the Administrative Procedure, excuse me, of the Voting Rights Act that any challenge of this sort would have to been brought in the District of Columbia.","start":1177.181,"stop":1190.395,"duration":13.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But of course, the Administrative Procedure Act allows you to sue the Attorney General anywhere that either a plaintiff or plaintiff reside.","start":1190.395,"stop":1199.09,"duration":8.69}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and I am not saying it as a closed question.","start":1199.09,"stop":1202.354,"duration":3.26},{"text":"I am saying that the Voting Rights Act Section 14(b) in indicating a venue directive for the District of Columbia might have been deemed to be controlling had a suit being brought to the Attorney General elsewhere despite the Administrative Procedure Act.","start":1202.354,"stop":1222.491,"duration":20.14},{"text":"It might have been argued under the kind of argument that prevails to some degree in the recent decision of this court in Sanders v. Califano.","start":1222.491,"stop":1232.951,"duration":10.46},{"text":"It might have been argued that Administrative Procedure Act does not create substantive jurisdiction and the substantive jurisdiction ordinarily would prevail had been limited by 14(b) of the Voting Rights Act.","start":1232.951,"stop":1245.416,"duration":12.46},{"text":"I think it is at least a grave question as to whether it could have been brought anywhere else and it seems to me that it was quite clear that it was highly appropriate to bring it here.","start":1245.416,"stop":1253.408,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well certainly, it would be unusual if it could be brought somewhere else.","start":1253.408,"stop":1256.301,"duration":2.89},{"text":"Wouldn’t it?","start":1256.301,"stop":1257.166,"duration":0.87},{"text":"If the state is limited to the District of Columbia and yet the plaintiffs in Harper v Levi in a review of the Attorney General’s action on the Administrative Procedure Act could sue in any venue in the country.","start":1257.166,"stop":1267.919,"duration":10.75}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the symmetry argument that has been made in the court below and the appellees, I think does not fit this statutory scheme.","start":1267.919,"stop":1281.208,"duration":13.29},{"text":"It is not a symmetrical statute.","start":1281.208,"stop":1283.106,"duration":1.9},{"text":"The complainants are not passing laws, the states are.","start":1283.106,"stop":1286.494,"duration":3.39},{"text":"The covered states have been found to be in a special category which requires them to go through procedures before they can create a valid law and they are given choices of procedure that they can go directly to the District Court in the District of Columbia or they can come to the Attorney General.","start":1286.494,"stop":1303.211,"duration":16.72},{"text":"And in view of the fact of Section 5 explicitly preserves the right of plaintiffs to bring Three-Judge District Court actions which would be in the state where you get jurisdiction of the state.","start":1303.211,"stop":1313.391,"duration":10.18},{"text":"And indeed, the very case that you have now before you is such a case.","start":1313.391,"stop":1318.206,"duration":4.81},{"text":"The South Carolina having elected to treat Harper v. Levi as nullity and having continued to enforce the statute which we say has not been cleared.","start":1318.206,"stop":1332.228,"duration":14.02},{"text":"Plaintiffs follow the only remedy available to them which was to bring a suit in a Three-Judge District Court of South Carolina.","start":1332.228,"stop":1338.231,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And I take it, you say that a state law would not be in effect during this review period.","start":1338.231,"stop":1349.192,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I think that the question of whether the law would go into effect in the review period might depend on the procedures along the way.","start":1349.192,"stop":1364.373,"duration":15.18},{"text":"I can conceive that --","start":1364.373,"stop":1365.935,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In any event, any court, I take it you say, could extend the time of the Attorney General.","start":1365.935,"stop":1374.965,"duration":9.03},{"text":"And any time they extended the time it just has not expired and the law has not gone into effect.","start":1374.965,"stop":1381.219,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I think, Your Honor, that a court with jurisdiction and assuming of course that the action is brought promptly because I can not conceive that someone could come along years later and attempt to stop enforcement.","start":1381.219,"stop":1393.579,"duration":12.36},{"text":"But any court which had jurisdiction and which issued an order extending the Attorney General's time for objection, I think would properly toll the enforceability of the statute.","start":1393.579,"stop":1407.937,"duration":14.36},{"text":"There was no effort made in the Harper case to stop the pending election.","start":1407.937,"stop":1411.925,"duration":3.99},{"text":"The statute has in fact been enforced by South Carolina, first in the 1972 Senate elections and then in the 1976.","start":1411.925,"stop":1420.927,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But if the Attorney General says that “I don’t want any more time, I am not going to object.”","start":1420.927,"stop":1428.306,"duration":7.38},{"text":"May court with jurisdiction as you say, extend his time at the suit of some private party.","start":1428.306,"stop":1436.998,"duration":8.69}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"We think, Your Honor, that if there is judicial review that it is clear that there has to be a power in the court to grant effective relief.","start":1436.998,"stop":1446.581,"duration":9.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So your answer is yes, that the state law would not be in effect throughout this review period on appeal maybe to this court.","start":1446.581,"stop":1457.902,"duration":11.32}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, Your Honor, that I hedged the answer before by saying that it would depend on the procedure if no stay of the act was asked and if the act had gone into effect before the court issued the order extending the time for objection then I assume that the act would stay in effect until the litigation was resolved or until a state order was issued.","start":1457.902,"stop":1488.075,"duration":30.17},{"text":"If the objection was told while the 60-day period had not been completed, as we contend was the case here, then we would agree that properly the act should not have been given effect during that period.","start":1488.075,"stop":1505.121,"duration":17.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If the state chooses to go to the Three-Judge Court in the District of Columbia, what about intervention by private parties?","start":1505.121,"stop":1514.849,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume that interested private parties --","start":1514.849,"stop":1517.081,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But do you know?","start":1517.081,"stop":1518.128,"duration":1.05},{"text":"Has there been a law on it or not?","start":1518.128,"stop":1522.722,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I am informed that there has been intervention of private parties permitted, for example, in the Richmond case.","start":1522.722,"stop":1531.097,"duration":8.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When the states sues, the state just --who is the defendant in that suit?","start":1531.097,"stop":1538.913,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"United States is the defendant.","start":1538.913,"stop":1540.723,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not the Attorney General?","start":1540.723,"stop":1541.842,"duration":1.12},{"text":"Just the United States?","start":1541.842,"stop":1543.694,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1543.694,"stop":1546.53,"duration":2.84},{"text":"The Attorney General’s role is the special role created by the statute in what we think were intended to be routine and easy cases where the state is saved the difficulty and burden of going through a whole court procedure.","start":1546.53,"stop":1561.347,"duration":14.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your interest in the case, I take it, is you think the standards of the Voting Rights Act are considerably different than the constitutional standard?","start":1561.347,"stop":1571.303,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"We think that there are certain clear differences.","start":1571.303,"stop":1575.887,"duration":4.58},{"text":"Perhaps the most significant difference is the burden of proof.","start":1575.887,"stop":1582.215,"duration":6.33},{"text":"A state is required to come forward and to establish that its law will not be discriminatory in purpose or effect.","start":1582.215,"stop":1592.632,"duration":10.42},{"text":"In a Fifteenth Amendment Case, the plaintiffs have the burden of coming forward and establishing violation of at least effect and possibly also purpose.","start":1592.632,"stop":1609.844,"duration":17.21},{"text":"And that difference in burden of proof is a very, very major difference.","start":1609.844,"stop":1613.25,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There was the difference in the substantive standard also, isn’t there?","start":1613.25,"stop":1616.028,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":1616.028,"stop":1616.729,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn’t there a difference also in the substantive standard?","start":1616.729,"stop":1621.078,"duration":4.35},{"text":"Doesn’t the Beers case indicate that?","start":1621.078,"stop":1623.225,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that it does Your Honor.","start":1623.225,"stop":1624.59,"duration":1.37},{"text":"Yes.","start":1624.59,"stop":1625.499,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I think that the Voting Rights Act has part of Congress power --","start":1625.499,"stop":1627.92,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It is more difficult than no matter who has the burden of proof.","start":1627.92,"stop":1632.154,"duration":4.23},{"text":"The standard of the Voting Rights Act has more stringent standard than that of either the Fourteenth or Fifteen Amendment, isn’t it?","start":1632.154,"stop":1639.613,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. J. Roger Wollenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that it is and I believe that in upholding that act that this court has clearly recognized, that Congress had power to implement the Fifteenth amendment by going somewhat beyond.","start":1639.613,"stop":1651.553,"duration":11.94},{"text":"I should like, if I may, preserve the rest of time for reply.","start":1651.553,"stop":1667.763,"duration":16.21}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Turner.","start":1667.763,"stop":1669.228,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the court.","start":1669.228,"stop":1673.967,"duration":4.74},{"text":"We believe that the petitioners should prevail in this case because the Attorney General’s objection to Act 1205 reapportioning the South Carolina State Senate was a valid objection under the Voting Rights Act.","start":1673.967,"stop":1690.715,"duration":16.75},{"text":"Although, the Attorney General initially determined himself to be without authority to express his independent view that this act deluded minority voting rights because of the decision of a three-judge reapportionment court in the Twiggs case.","start":1690.715,"stop":1707.007,"duration":16.29},{"text":"The matter was promptly brought to the attention of the District Court for the District of Columbia which ordered the Attorney General to use his own discretion and he did so.","start":1707.007,"stop":1717.89,"duration":10.88},{"text":"Subsequent decisions of this court confirm that the District of Columbia Courts in Harper were right and that the Attorney General’s deferral policy was wrong.","start":1717.89,"stop":1731.445,"duration":13.55},{"text":"The fundamental question here then is whether the Attorney General's mistake of law was properly and legally corrected by the Harper Courts.","start":1731.445,"stop":1742.053,"duration":10.61},{"text":"If so, the objection stands and Act 1205 may not be implemented legally under the act.","start":1742.053,"stop":1748.48,"duration":6.43},{"text":"If not, the court below was right, and its judgment should be affirmed.","start":1748.48,"stop":1754.032,"duration":5.55},{"text":"In the limited time available, I would like to address the following issues: First, whether the Voting Rights Act contemplates an independent review by the Attorney General of submitted legislative changes.","start":1754.032,"stop":1770.431,"duration":16.4},{"text":"Secondly, whether the Voting Rights Act properly construed permits the traditional remedy in the nature of mandamus to compel the exercise of administrative discretion.","start":1770.431,"stop":1783.628,"duration":13.2},{"text":"And third, whether relief, such as that granted by the Harper court would be disruptive to the administration of the act.","start":1783.628,"stop":1794.111,"duration":10.48},{"text":"The independent review is contemplated by the act we argue because it is inherent in the statutory scheme which congress has provided us.","start":1794.111,"stop":1803.648,"duration":9.54},{"text":"The Attorney General is a substitute or a surrogate for a declaratory judgment proceeding.","start":1803.648,"stop":1810.151,"duration":6.5},{"text":"It is a quick 60-day review but it is a review on the merits.","start":1810.151,"stop":1815.969,"duration":5.82},{"text":"Whether the change is discriminatory, is the issue for the Attorney General.","start":1815.969,"stop":1821.809,"duration":5.84},{"text":"Certainly, Congress believed and had the right to believe that the Attorney General would do some reviewing and not merely look at it or decide that he was not going to review anything.","start":1821.809,"stop":1836.305,"duration":14.5},{"text":"He was, after all, given the job to be a surrogate for the District Court of the District of Columbia.","start":1836.305,"stop":1842.677,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you have to say Mr. Turner about the argument advanced by your friends on the other side of the table?","start":1842.677,"stop":1852.131,"duration":9.45},{"text":"At Page 27 of their briefs, that one of your predecessors testified before the Congress, I assume the Judiciary Committee, asking for an amendment, first, to give more time to the Attorney General under Section 5 and the second, to provide for a judicial review.","start":1852.131,"stop":1878.466,"duration":26.33},{"text":"The Congress declined that invitation.","start":1878.466,"stop":1883.453,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"There are two comments there, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1883.453,"stop":1887.784,"duration":4.33},{"text":"First, the proposal was for review on the merit.","start":1887.784,"stop":1892.093,"duration":4.31},{"text":"Here we are talking about a much more limited kind of review, so I don’t think the two proposals are parallel.","start":1892.093,"stop":1899.69,"duration":7.6},{"text":"And secondly, Congress rejected it.","start":1899.69,"stop":1902.484,"duration":2.79},{"text":"So it was not passed that the Attorney General’s decision on the merits should be reviewed.","start":1902.484,"stop":1909.993,"duration":7.51},{"text":"And I again stress, it is not what we are talking about in this case, we are talking about very limited mandamus type review in the District Court of the District of Columbia.","start":1909.993,"stop":1923.029,"duration":13.04}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"If I understand it, the essence of your argument is that it is reviewable because it was an erroneous determination.","start":1923.029,"stop":1931.766,"duration":8.74},{"text":"Does that not have something to do with the merits?","start":1931.766,"stop":1935.736,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"It has in this sense, Your Honor, that as we advised this court in the Georgia litigation, if you recall that and Footnote 6 in that opinion sets forth how the Attorney General and the courts were trying to accommodate at the intersection of reapportionment litigation and Section 5 litigation.","start":1935.736,"stop":1957.211,"duration":21.47},{"text":"And one of the policies that we expressed at that time was one of deferral.","start":1957.211,"stop":1961.866,"duration":4.65},{"text":"In our brief in that case, we indicated that that policy of deferral was under attack on the Harper litigation.","start":1961.866,"stop":1971.77,"duration":9.9},{"text":"Since then the Harper litigation has decided that that policy was wrong and we were ordered to stop it and this court confirmed that judgment in Connor versus Waller and we now accept it.","start":1971.77,"stop":1985.774,"duration":14},{"text":"We have always thought this multimember system was dilutive in abridge minority voting rights.","start":1985.774,"stop":1991.791,"duration":6.02},{"text":"We did not express that opinion solely out of deference to the three-judge court in the Twiggs litigation.","start":1991.791,"stop":1997.974,"duration":6.18},{"text":"That deference turned out that we were not only wrong, we were dead wrong.","start":1997.974,"stop":2001.917,"duration":3.94},{"text":"The deference should have gone the other way and in Waller, this court said that district Courts in that situation should defer to the Attorney General until his determination has been made.","start":2001.917,"stop":2015.522,"duration":13.61},{"text":"So that it is a basic mistake of law to defer, I think, Mr. Justice that we are talking about here and not review of particular decisions made by the Attorney General.","start":2015.522,"stop":2035.451,"duration":19.93},{"text":"The record here indicates that this is the only case in which the Attorney General followed this policy of deferral.","start":2035.451,"stop":2044.176,"duration":8.72},{"text":"On page 31 of the Appendix, the position of the Chief of the Voting Section of the Civil Rights Division established that this Harper case or this South Carolina Act 1205 is the only one in which that deferral policy, a very short lived policy was followed.","start":2044.176,"stop":2066.021,"duration":21.85},{"text":"So the case is one of a kind.","start":2066.021,"stop":2069.132,"duration":3.11},{"text":"The Voting Rights Act --","start":2069.132,"stop":2069.742,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Makes one wonder, why we granted certiorari?","start":2069.742,"stop":2073.686,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, its importance and I am not in a position to know why you accepted the appeal.","start":2073.686,"stop":2084.978,"duration":11.29},{"text":"But I think it is important to establish whether or not there is this limited kind of mandamus or arbitrary and capricious review potential over the Attorney General’s administration of this Act.","start":2084.978,"stop":2103.356,"duration":18.38},{"text":"The Harper suit was based on 28 USC 1361 that was recited in the complaint and then recited in the Court of Appeals opinion that very unequivocally gives the District Court’s jurisdiction to compel the performance of official duties owed to the plaintiffs.","start":2103.356,"stop":2127.406,"duration":24.05},{"text":"This kind of action has been described and recognized in this courts opinions as “the familiar rule that a court may exercise its equity powers or equivalent mandamus powers to compel courts boards or officers to act in a manner with respect to which they may have jurisdiction or authority”, although, to address your concern Mr. Chief Justice, the court will not assume control or guide the exercise of that authority.","start":2127.406,"stop":2159.69,"duration":32.28},{"text":"That is out of Virginian Railway Company in 300 U.S.","start":2159.69,"stop":2164.781,"duration":5.09},{"text":"This kind of review is explicitly recognized in the Administrative procedures Act, Section 7061 which says that the reviewing court shall compel agency action unlawfully withheld and courts require, as you know, convincing evidence before that kind of review is withheld.","start":2164.781,"stop":2190.556,"duration":25.78},{"text":"So unless the Voting Rights Act precludes such relief that this rule ought to control this case, in our review and to address the venue question, I think 14(b), suggests strongly that this District of Columbia Court was the only proper venue.","start":2190.556,"stop":2211.018,"duration":20.46},{"text":"But we have found nothing in either the terms of the act or its purpose with the legislative history that indicates a view that congress intended to foreclose this kind of limited review.","start":2211.018,"stop":2223.758,"duration":12.74},{"text":"It is true that a great amount of discretion is vested in the Attorney General.","start":2223.758,"stop":2230.25,"duration":6.49},{"text":"The distinction is that the mandamus compels him to exercise it and does not tell him how.","start":2230.25,"stop":2236.58,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think Mr. Turner that if the state submits a plan to the Attorney General, he rejects or objects to it in 60 days and the state does not bring any suit in the District Court, it just kind of accepts the Attorney General’s rejection, that private plaintiffs in the state could bring in action to review the Attorney Generals objection under the Administrative Procedure Act?","start":2236.58,"stop":2262.278,"duration":25.7}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"I know of no precise authority or precedent on that Mr. Justice.","start":2262.278,"stop":2267.903,"duration":5.63},{"text":"The nearest, there has been was an attempt by New York legislators to come to Washington and seek relief from an objection, the Attorney General had entered and the District Court of the District of Columbia, in that case, indicated that they had no standing to seek such relief.","start":2267.903,"stop":2293.189,"duration":25.29},{"text":"That is as close as the hypothetically posed, I think, has been addressed.","start":2293.189,"stop":2299.905,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Turner, does the statute require the Attorney General to give a statement of reasons for either an objection or a non-objection?","start":2299.905,"stop":2306.174,"duration":6.27},{"text":"I know, he does this as a matter of policy.","start":2306.174,"stop":2307.792,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"He does as a matter of policy.","start":2307.792,"stop":2309.324,"duration":1.53},{"text":"He has announced that policy in the guidelines the statute does not require.","start":2309.324,"stop":2313.995,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If he should change that policy would you say that the existence to review would compel him to adapt the policy?","start":2313.995,"stop":2320.629,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it probably would.","start":2320.629,"stop":2323.184,"duration":2.56},{"text":"I am thinking of the Bachowski type litigation where and certainly under the Freedom of Information Act, this kind of information underlying administrative rulings are available to the public and would regardless of whether the Attorney General announced or did not announce this --","start":2323.184,"stop":2349.355,"duration":26.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If in his letter that he did write here instead of saying he was constrained to follow the Three-Judge Court, if instead of that, he said, I think as a matter of discretion, a sound policy to do the same thing the District Court did.","start":2349.355,"stop":2362.103,"duration":12.75},{"text":"Would that have been reviewable?","start":2362.103,"stop":2364.498,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"If that was his independent judgment that is what we are talking about here because we have --.","start":2364.498,"stop":2370.635,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your position depended on a reading of that letter that he felt legally bound to follow that.","start":2370.635,"stop":2375.078,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that is correct and he recalled that Act 1205 was preceded by Act 932.","start":2375.078,"stop":2382.816,"duration":7.74},{"text":"Act 932 has the same features as Act 1205.","start":2382.816,"stop":2387.883,"duration":5.07},{"text":"Act 932, the Attorney General objected to because there was no intervening court decision.","start":2387.883,"stop":2394.954,"duration":7.07},{"text":"When there was a court decision, and we had gone down to South Carolina at the court’s invitation and told them of our view and told them of the basis for the objection and the court rejected our views and said that there was not any Fifteenth Amendment violation there.","start":2394.954,"stop":2415.305,"duration":20.35},{"text":"So we were right at the intersection that I was trying to describe to the Chief Justice where we had to decide whether to follow the court or to try to overrule the court and we decided to try to follow it.","start":2415.305,"stop":2427.321,"duration":12.02},{"text":"Later under this court’s rules, the precedents and who is to differ to whom has been made quite clear.","start":2427.321,"stop":2437.024,"duration":9.7},{"text":"We have no interest in pursuing the matter.","start":2437.024,"stop":2439.701,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I repeat the question, I thought Mr. Justice Stevens was asking?","start":2439.701,"stop":2444.513,"duration":4.81},{"text":"Let us assume that the Attorney General had written a letter within the 60-day period in which in substance he said “I think the reapportionment plan fully comports with the law.","start":2444.513,"stop":2454.863,"duration":10.35},{"text":"You have my authority to proceed with it.","start":2454.863,"stop":2458.024,"duration":3.16},{"text":"Is your contention that there would still be review by these parties under the APA?","start":2458.024,"stop":2464.509,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2464.509,"stop":2466.257,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your answer would be the same, if the Attorney General did nothing within the 60 days?","start":2466.257,"stop":2471.606,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"If he did nothing within the 60 days, it depends why he did nothing.","start":2471.606,"stop":2475.683,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose he just said nothing.","start":2475.683,"stop":2477.239,"duration":1.56},{"text":"He would just let the 60 days go by like an ordinary statute of limitations.","start":2477.239,"stop":2483.867,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"The whole administrative practice under this is to say something.","start":2483.867,"stop":2490.04,"duration":6.17},{"text":"So it is very hard for me to cope with the question that says the Attorney General stands mute.","start":2490.04,"stop":2495.449,"duration":5.41},{"text":"We have a whole section that analyzes each one of these things as they come in and reaches a determination on it.","start":2495.449,"stop":2503.311,"duration":7.86},{"text":"If it fell in somebody’s waste basket, on the first day, that the submission came in and was never picked up and the 60 days expired it might be a more understandable hypothetical for us.","start":2503.311,"stop":2517.856,"duration":14.55},{"text":"In that situation, I think mandamus would lie because the Attorney General had not done the kind of independent review that congress envisioned in the statute.","start":2517.856,"stop":2529.117,"duration":11.26},{"text":"And I hope that that --","start":2529.117,"stop":2531.641,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Take another hypothetical.","start":2531.641,"stop":2535.011,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Suppose, the Attorney General had ruled in favor of the Harper plaintiffs originally within the 60-day period?","start":2535.011,"stop":2544.897,"duration":9.89},{"text":"I agree that the state of South Carolina would have had no remedy other than as prescribed by the Act to come before a Three-Judge Court in the district.","start":2544.897,"stop":2554.75,"duration":9.85},{"text":"Let us assume that say a state senator in South Carolina who would lose his seat decided that the Attorney General had made a gross error of law.","start":2554.75,"stop":2565.315,"duration":10.57},{"text":"Would he have the same right that Mr. Harper had to institute an action under the Administrative Procedure Act challenging the Attorney General’s decision on a legal ground?","start":2565.315,"stop":2581.203,"duration":15.89}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me that if the objection was made for a very fundamentally wrong reason, as we have in this case, where the Attorney General mistakenly thought himself without authority to rule.","start":2581.203,"stop":2599.227,"duration":18.02},{"text":"If somehow, a basic mistake such as that resulted in an objection and the person injured by the Attorney General’s failure to do his duty, I think would have the same kind of limited restricted review that we are talking about in this case.","start":2599.227,"stop":2621.726,"duration":22.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that right be limited by any period of limitations?","start":2621.726,"stop":2627.92,"duration":6.19},{"text":"Could it have been brought a year later?","start":2627.92,"stop":2630.54,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the normal rule of laches has to apply here and I can not probe the outer limits of that because this was filed within 30 days of even the day the 60 days expired that expired.","start":2630.54,"stop":2644.176,"duration":13.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Turner can I just ask one more question because Mr. Justice Powell followed up on a thought that I had; you answered him by saying if the letter by the Attorney General said I am not going to object because I find that the plan is lawful on all respects that would not be reviewable, I understood you to say.","start":2644.176,"stop":2660.539,"duration":16.36},{"text":"What if they made a clearer law and he was wrong?","start":2660.539,"stop":2663.881,"duration":3.34},{"text":"Somebody came and said that legally your answer is just dead wrong just as it was here.","start":2663.881,"stop":2668.822,"duration":4.94},{"text":"Why would that be different?","start":2668.822,"stop":2670.19,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"It is different because of the distinction that we see in the cases dealing with mandamus, where they say the issue is whether the discretion has been exercised.","start":2670.19,"stop":2684.622,"duration":14.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"but the question whether it is lawful or unlawful is not a question of discretion, is it?","start":2684.622,"stop":2688.505,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that is what we are saying.","start":2688.505,"stop":2690.073,"duration":1.57},{"text":"This is a threshold kind of thing.","start":2690.073,"stop":2691.429,"duration":1.36},{"text":"The Attorney General said I have no discretion to review this in effect because the record --.","start":2691.429,"stop":2695.996,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But what if he says I have discretion to review it.","start":2695.996,"stop":2698.048,"duration":2.05},{"text":"I have reviewed it and find it is lawful.","start":2698.048,"stop":2700.376,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I think that is the discretion that Congress gave him and it ought to sustain.","start":2700.376,"stop":2703.927,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though he has made a plainly erroneous ruling of law?","start":2703.927,"stop":2707.264,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"If that was shown I still think that in that case Congress has presumed the Attorney General is going to exercise his discretion, he will exercise it correctly and in those few cases where he does not exercise it correctly the constitutional litigation is the proper remedy.","start":2707.264,"stop":2725.597,"duration":18.33}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well Mr. Turner.","start":2725.597,"stop":2729.317,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Turner","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2729.317,"stop":2730.29,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bell.","start":2730.29,"stop":2732.469,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Will you please like to tell us what you are going to tell us tomorrow morning.","start":2732.469,"stop":2738.584,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"It looks as though, I will have to save most of my argument until then Mr. Chief Justice and if it pleases the court, I think perhaps in the short time I have allotted.","start":2738.584,"stop":2751.513,"duration":12.93},{"text":"I am sorry.","start":2751.513,"stop":2752.028,"duration":0.51},{"text":"Perhaps I misunderstood you.","start":2752.028,"stop":2753.463,"duration":1.44},{"text":"Do you wish me to proceed for five minutes?","start":2753.463,"stop":2756.429,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2756.429,"stop":2757.732,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps that time could be most properly used answering some questions that have been posed while they are fresh in the minds of the court.","start":2757.732,"stop":2765.733,"duration":8},{"text":"We find it very puzzling that the United States is taking some of the positions it has taken here this afternoon because the opposite positions are being taken in other litigation at this time or have been taken since the Harper case was decided.","start":2765.733,"stop":2783.824,"duration":18.09},{"text":"For example, the question of whether a mistake of law is reviewable was presented in a case called Harris against the United States, here in the District of Columbia District Court.","start":2783.824,"stop":2796.344,"duration":12.52},{"text":"That case is reported in 415 Federal Supplement and the Attorney General in that case, which is a post Waller case, took exactly the opposite position.","start":2796.344,"stop":2805.575,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Several questions were raised as to whether he has committed fundamental errors of law.","start":2805.575,"stop":2811.311,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Among the allegations with it, he had addressed himself to the question of the one person one vote standard in a Section 5 review.","start":2811.311,"stop":2820.374,"duration":9.06},{"text":"It was claimed that Section 5 does not authorize him to get into the one person one vote standard.","start":2820.374,"stop":2827.086,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"We think the case involved of the threshold question of the reviewability of his failure to object.","start":2827.086,"stop":2834.275,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"It involved the question of his withdrawing an objection and the basic claim being made by the plaintiffs, Mr. Justice Stewart, was that he had withdrawn an objection with no new evidence being placed before him.","start":2834.275,"stop":2846.329,"duration":12.05}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any question as to whether that was reviewable?","start":2846.329,"stop":2851.778,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Randall T. Bell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2851.778,"stop":2852.234,"duration":0.46},{"text":"That was the threshold question which was presented.","start":2852.234,"stop":2854.983,"duration":2.75},{"text":"The Attorney General said no, this is not reviewable.","start":2854.983,"stop":2858.074,"duration":3.09},{"text":"The position we are taking in this case, the court found against him in part citing Harper against Levi and for him in parts.","start":2858.074,"stop":2866.218,"duration":8.14},{"text":"But we see no distinction between the questions raised in Harris and the kind of question that was raised in Harper against Levi.","start":2866.218,"stop":2874.063,"duration":7.85},{"text":"We do see an inconsistency of position.","start":2874.063,"stop":2878.049,"duration":3.99},{"text":"Now I also understood Mr. Turner to say that if an objection is fundamentally wrong, an objection of the opposite case from Harper v. Levi where the Attorney General said no objection.","start":2878.049,"stop":2890.96,"duration":12.91},{"text":"But if an objection is fundamentally wrong I understood him to say that yes, in that case private parties could seek review of that.","start":2890.96,"stop":2898.542,"duration":7.58},{"text":"Now of course the same judge that ruled against the Attorney General on that issue in Harper v. Levi found the other way when that question was presented in Griffith.","start":2898.542,"stop":2909.831,"duration":11.29},{"text":"But beyond that in a case called Robinson v. Potenger, we find that the Attorney General took the opposite position on that as well.","start":2909.831,"stop":2923.269,"duration":13.44},{"text":"There are some officials in Montgomery, Alabama were again raising some of these questions.","start":2923.269,"stop":2929.713,"duration":6.44},{"text":"He said in that case we cannot even be made parties to this suit.","start":2929.713,"stop":2933.878,"duration":4.16},{"text":"That is how immune we are from court review, much less getting into these questions of law.","start":2933.878,"stop":2938.485,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will resume there at 10 o’clock tomorrow morning.","start":2938.485,"stop":2949.982,"duration":11.5}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Apr  18 - 19, 1977","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"75-1583","citation":"432 US 491 (1977)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/432/491","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 20, 1977"}